  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2047984403" />
    <a title="Deanna " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15662887-deanna"><img alt="Deanna " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1437589889p2/15662887.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2047984403?book_show_action=true">Jul 03, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Deanna " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Deanna " href="/user/show/15662887-deanna">Deanna </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2047984403" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16620094987010243184">My reviews can also be seen at: <a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://deesradreadsandreviews.wordpress.com/'>https://deesradreadsandreviews.wordpr...</a><br/><br/>2.5 Stars<br/><br/>I really struggling with a rating for this book. I think I landed on 2.5 because I was caught up in the story and had to know how it was going to end. However, I did have some issues with it. <br/><br/>When I read the description for Fierce Kingdom I was really looking forward to reading it. It sounded like it was going to be an intense read. <br/><br/>Joan is relaxing with her four-year-old son, Lincoln in one of their favorite areas </span>
  <span id="freeText16620094987010243184" style="display:none">My reviews can also be seen at: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://deesradreadsandreviews.wordpress.com/">https://deesradreadsandreviews.wordpr...</a><br /><br />2.5 Stars<br /><br />I really struggling with a rating for this book. I think I landed on 2.5 because I was caught up in the story and had to know how it was going to end. However, I did have some issues with it. <br /><br />When I read the description for Fierce Kingdom I was really looking forward to reading it. It sounded like it was going to be an intense read. <br /><br />Joan is relaxing with her four-year-old son, Lincoln in one of their favorite areas of the zoo. She is listening to him chatter about Dr. Doom and Batman. It's near closing time and so they start to head for the exit....the next moment she hears what sounds like popping balloons or firecrackers. As she continues to head towards the exit she sees something that makes her turn around and run. <br /><br />For the next three hours she must run, hide, and make some tough decisions to keep herself and her son safe. <br /><br />When the book started off it was really intense. I can't imagine being in such a terrifying situation. Trying to keep yourself AND your child calm at a time like that would be extremely stressful. I kept trying to picture my zoo and tried to figure out where I would hide with my child. <br /><br />Most of the story is told from the mother, Joan's point of view, but we also hear from other characters, including a teenager, Kailynn who works in the zoo's restaurant and a retired elementary schoolteacher, Margaret Powell. As the story progresses we learn quite a bit about Lincoln and the relationship between mother and son. We also hear about Kailynn's life and her relationship with her father. Margaret Powel isn't as developed but we still get a sense of her life as a school teacher and how she felt about her students. <br /><br />As I mentioned the beginning of the book was extremely tense. I found midway that it started to drag a bit...but then it really picked up again towards the end. <br /><br />I struggled with a few things ....<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[The mother had a phone and I understand she didn't want them to see the light but that would have been solved by turning it off and waiting for a time to use it later. But to throw the phone away? Also she spoke only with her husband when she did have the chance to use her phone. Why not call the police too? I know the police were aware of the situation but the phone could have helped let them know where exactly she was in the zoo. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />I also thought that there were a few things left unexplained. Some loose ends.... <br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[What happened to the baby? What happened to the teacher? <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br />Although maybe the author wants readers to come to their own conclusions. <br /><br />All that being said, not once did I think about not finishing the novel. Honestly, I was engrossed and had to know how this was going to turn out. I barely put it down. I read this book in about three sittings. I think that a lot of people will love this book, but some of it just wasn't for me. <br /><br />Something that really bothered me:<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[One of the characters talks about when her father was younger that he would catch cats (23 of them) and swing them by their tails onto rooftops. A few pages later same character mentions this again, as she imagines her father swinging cats like a discus, and how he said he felt so satisfied when he let loose and it sailed through the air. I realize some parts were written to make a point (many psychopaths often abused animals in their childhood). I understand that many authors often use violence to make a point. And some readers are able to skip over it, others can't read it at all, and others are able to read and let it go. We are all different. Usually I'm able to skim over it (though not always). I'm just trying to say we are all different. So maybe this won't bother anyone else. But my issue with this was when I read the Acknowledgments it said "Thanks to, 'such and such' for his Cat Escapades" This brought me up short. Because if the "swinging cats by the tail up on to rooftops" was based on someone who did this? I'm not sure what to say. Of course I could be wrong...... But there were no other mention of cats and it seems very coincidental. But if I am wrong then I'm wrong. Maybe I'm being overly sensitive but I just didn't care for that. This is only my opinion though <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Many thanks to Random House Canada for providing a copy of this book for me to read in exchange for my honest review.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16620094987010243184" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


